{"cursor":"5369","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nA 'vapour' (British spelling) or 'vapor' (see spelling differences) is a\nsubstance in the gas phase at a temperature lower than its critical\npoint. R. H. Petrucci, W. S. Harwood, and F. G. Herring, \"General\nChemistry\", 8th edition (Prentice-Hall 2002), p.486. This means that the\nvapour can be condensed to a liquid or to a solid by increasing its pressure\nwithout reducing the temperature.\n\nFor example, water has a critical temperature of 374 Â°C (647 K), which is the\nhighest temperature at which liquid water can exist. In the atmosphere at\nordinary temperatures, therefore, gaseous water (known as water vapor) will\ncondense to liquid if its partial pressure is increased sufficiently.\n\nA vapour may co-exist with a liquid (or solid). When this is true, the two\nphases will be in equilibrium, and the gas pressure will equal the equilibrium\nvapour pressure of the liquid (or solid). Petrucci et al. p.483\n","linknr":275,"url":"vapor","recorded":1362569389,"links":66,"instances":["unit","fog","equation","perfumery"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Gases","Pressure","Chemical properties"],"headings":["Properties","Vapour pressure","Examples","Measuring vapour","Vapours of flammable liquids","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/37/Watervapor_cup.jpg/220px-Watervapor_cup.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/34/Phase-diag2.svg/300px-Phase-diag2.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/Binary_Boiling_Point_Diagram_new.svg/220px-Binary_Boiling_Point_Diagram_new.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c0/Crepuscular_Rays_Beam_through_the_Mist_Blown_from_Takkakaw_Falls.jpg/220p